'''''Athos II''''' was a passenger and cargo liner for [[Compagnie des Messageries Maritimes]] making her maiden voyage from Marseilles 25 March 1927 starting on the line's Far East service serving Marseilles, Malaya, Indo-China, Hong Kong, Shanghai, Kobe and Yokohama. The ship, laid down in 1923 and launched 12 November 1925, had been completed by [[AG Weser|Aktien-Gesellschaft „Weser"]], Bremen and delivered to the French as part of [[World War I reparations]].{{sfn|''New York Evening Post'' (November 17, 1925)}}{{sfn|Swiggum & Kohli 2012}} After a 1937 refit, including boilers increasing speed to {{convert|19|knots|mph km/h|1}}, ''Athos II'' resumed Far East service.

The ship started [[World War II]] in French national service until captured by the Allies in North Africa and then being turned over to the United States [[War Shipping Administration]] by [[Free French]] authorities at [[Casablanca]] for operation as a troop transport allocated to the United States Army until returned to the French government in March 1946.

''Athos II'' transported French troops to [[French Indochina]], Korea, during the [[Suez Crisis|Suez intervention]] and lastly Algeria in the postwar years as well as a period carrying North African pilgrims to [[Jeddah]].{{sfn|Swiggum & Kohli 2012}} 

==World War II==
===French national service===
At the outbreak of World War II ''Athos II'' was still on the Far Eastern route but on 1 February 1940 at [[Colombo]], [[Sri Lanka|Celyon]] joined the Australian/New Zealand convoy, designated US1 for secrecy and transporting about 13,500 troops to North Africa, under an escort then led by {{HMS|Ramillies|07|6}}.{{sfn|Gill|1957|pp=84, 93—94}} After passage through the [[Suez Canal]] and return to France ''Athos II'' began Marseilles, Egypt and Syria service until the 22 June 1940 [[Armistice of 22 June 1940|German-French armistice]] when the ship was laid up at [[Alexandria, Egypt]] along with other French ships seized in the Suez Canal and Egyptian waters. In addition to the merchant ships was a French naval force, Force X, under Admiral [[Rene-Emile Godfroy]] that had been operating with the British fleet out of Alexandria.{{sfn|Titterton|Brown|2002|p=33}} After the [[Battle of France|fall of France]] with German controlled [[Vichy France]] controlling French ports the French were faced with the options of continuing with the Allies under [[Charles de Gaulle|General  de Gaulle]], demilitarizing or being sunk by the British.{{sfn|Titterton|Brown|2002|p=34}} The British action against the French fleet at [[Attack on Mers-el-Kébir|Oran]] stalled demilitarization but that resumed after further negotiations with the result reduction of French fleet's manpower, some 4,000 men, to one-third was required.{{sfn|Titterton|Brown|2002|p=34}} Two thousand French sailors had already left Alexandria when ''Athos II'' was allowed to sail on 13 July 1940 with the 1,000 remaining personnel of Force X and some merchant crew members to France.{{sfn|Titterton|Brown|2002|p=34}} In September 1940 repatriated French troops from [[Syria]] and then became the guard ship at [[Algiers]] until captured by the Allies in November 1942 during [[Operation Torch]].{{sfn|Swiggum & Kohli 2012}}{{sfn|Association French Lines}}

===Allied service with United States War Shipping Administration===
On 8 March 1943 ''Athos II'' was turned over to United States War Shipping Administration (WSA) control by French Authorities at Casablanca and on 1 April 1943 began operation as a WSA transport allocated to the United States Army and operated by French Lines, Inc. as agent.{{sfn|MARAD Vessel Status Card: ''Athos II''}}<ref group=note>Though never bareboat chartered to or operated by the Army the association was such that the ship is sometimes seen as USAT ''Athos II''.</ref>

''Athos II'' underwent conversion May—November of 1943 for WSA troop service by Turbine Engineering Corporation of New York.{{sfn|Charles|1947|p=284}} In December the ship made a voyage to the United Kingdom, returning in January, 1944.{{sfn|Charles|1947|p=284}} On 21 January 1944 the ship left New York for the [[Southwest Pacific Theater|Southwest Pacific]] but engine trouble forced a return to Panama from the [[Galápagos Islands]] before again getting underway on 8 March.{{sfn|Charles|1947|p=284}} In continuing the round-the-world trip ''Athos II'' then called at [[Bora Bora]], [[Fremantle]], [[Bombay]], [[Cape Town]], departing 8 May but again having to undergo repairs until 9 June, crossing  the Atlantic to [[Recife]] to arrive 1 July 1944 in New York.{{sfn|Charles|1947|p=284}} Subsequent operations were between New York and [[Naples]], [[Le Havre]], [[Southampton]] and [[Plymouth]].{{sfn|Charles|1947|p=284}} After two round trips to Naples the ship underwent extensive repairs in New York before resuming operations in February 1945.{{sfn|Charles|1947|p=284}} On a return from a Le Havre and Southampton voyage the ship again suffered engine problems and had to put in to [[Horta, Azores]] in December 1945 where troops were transferred to {{USS|Enterprise|CV-6|6}}.{{sfn|Charles|1947|p=284}} ''Athos II'' returned to New York after repairs and was released from troop transport service January 1946 to be returned to French authorities by WSA.{{sfn|Charles|1947|p=284}}

==Return to French service==
On 23 March 1946 ''Athos II'' was turned over to the French Shipping Mission at New York.{{sfn|MARAD Vessel Status Card: ''Athos II''}} 

